\f0\fs24 \cf0 A pitch deck is simply just that--another company figuring out a way to get financial resources from an investor.\
\
But what we are after is simply something that money cannot buy. Often times, I think far back into my life and the struggles and lessons learned and ask myself--What is it that I need that I cannot buy.\
\
{{\NeXTGraphic 06125bf8-44ca-4ecf-bda7-21ff9a4966cf.jpeg \width8000 \height6040 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}¬}\
\
I came to the states as a refuge in the 80s during a period of war and dissidents.\
\
I thank the heavens for this wonderful opportunity to get educated in America and having such an opportunity that I would never have had back in Cambodia.\
\
But people never always start on the same level playing ground. We were poor. Our sponsors deserted us and we were left being janitors and living off food stamps and welfare.  I remember I was wandering downtown with my cousin not even of age 5 or 6 hunting for recycled bottles. Back then, there weren't as many that were recyclable as there it is now, and the level of disappointments filled our eyes quickly when we found cans without the 3 arrow recyclable logo.\
\
Public education never had that 1:1 teacher student relationship.\
\
When I saw kids going on field trips to the zoo that our family could not afford, I simply stayed back and tried to read the unknown characters on my book. I remember one teacher felt so bad for us, she tried to call my parents who were at work--unreachable, and ended up paying out of pocket for my field trip money to Canobie Lake Park.  She was teary, but I was young, and I could only cry with her--not even knowing the reason for her tears.  This moment of consoling someone who pitied me without understanding why made a mark in my life.\
\
But I bit my lip--and here I am telling you that these moments of struggle and hardship to put myself through 3 jobs and school at the age of 16--has not made me more resilient: it has taught me unteachable wisdom.  So I finished college as a double major and even finished my masters in AI back in the early 2000s.  It has empowered me to try to make an impact to the world we live in.\
\
Lesson 1: Not everyone has opportunities or the drive to a high level of education during my youth.\
Lesson 2: Not everyone needs money for a good education, they need the right way to learn.\
and Lesson 3:  AI is our new opportunity not just to America, but to the whole world.\
\
And this leads me to the actual pitch deck.\
AI in education is changing how we learn, how we struggle, and how we survive.  It puts everyone on this even playing field, and it's only a matter of time where everyone will have their own custom AI buddy, unique to their level of knowledge and social growth.\
\
This is what we are building at Salareen.  We are building this level of AI far beyond just ChatGPT or Claude, where it is personable--our friend.  The friend who is  there helping you with opportunities so you don't need to dig from trash cans. The friend who teaches and grows with you as you come of age or get your first job. We are building the AI learning ecosystem for critical thinking, your buddy who always remembers everything you do, your buddy who reinforces your learning and awareness so you can say, "Oh yeah, we did that together 12 years ago and I remember how you taught me about the birds and the bees before I met my current wife".  Education is no longer a course in a classroom--knowledge, memory, heartfelt emotions, and unteachable wisdom moments is what Salareen is about. We want to change nearly 200 years of classroom repetition to unteachable wisdom unique to every individual on the planet including Mars.\
\
